[[File:Young people texting on smartphones using thumbs.JPG|thumb|300px|Texting with thumbs.]] [[File:Japanese women texting.jpg|thumb|300px|Japanese woman texting.]] '''Thumb tribe''' or sometimes '''thumb generation'''<ref>Note: ''oyayubizoku'' is the term in Japan</ref> is a term used to describe a younger generation with members who are more adept at [[texting]] using their thumbs than talking on the phone.<ref name=Brooke>CHRIS BROOKE, Daily Mail, [http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-106561/The-thumb-tribe.html The thumb tribe], Accessed June 19, 2014, "..In Japan, ... young people have been nicknamed the 'thumb tribe' or the 'thumb generation'.."</ref><ref name=Wang>JENNIFER WANG, NOVEMBER 23, 2010, Entrepreneur, [http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/217560 Jargon: Thumb Tribe: Dexterous individuals who text better (and faster) than they talk.], Accessed June 19, 2014</ref><ref name=Tharp>Mike Tharp, October 9, 2010, Merced Sun-Star, [http://www.mercedsunstar.com/2010/10/09/1603472/mike-tharp-maddies-inspiration.html Mike Tharp: Maddie's inspiration -- blanketing Merced], Accessed June 19, 2014, "...We thought this younger generation -- the Thumb Tribe with their texts, tweets, tats and taggers.."</ref><ref name=Allison>Kirsty Allison, 3ammagazine, [http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/3am-asia-rise-of-the-nu-mohemians/ rise of the nu mohemians], Accessed June 19, 2014, "...“It’s a marketing dream,” says Tadashi, ... We call them the Oyayubizoku generation (the thumb tribe)..."</ref> It identifies a trend among young people who use mobile phones for many activities, such as texting, email, entertainment and conversations, as opposed to using keyboards with traditional desktop computers.<ref name=AdAge>H. MARTIN CALLE, NOVEMBER 29, 2007, Advertising Age, [http://advertising-age.blogspot.com/2007/11/multi-cultural-marketing-ii-thumb-tribe.html Multi-Cultural Marketing: The Thumb Tribe], Accessed June 19, 2014, "..'THUMB TRIBE' referring to the masses of young people around the world ..."</ref> The term has been used by marketers to identify younger consumers.<ref name="AdAge"/> It marks a shift in the favorite digit, such that activities typically done by the forefinger, such as pointing at things or ringing doorbells, are being done with the [[thumb]].<ref name=AmeliaHill>Amelia Hill of The Observer, 23 March 2002, The Guardian, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2002/mar/24/mobilephones.games Thumbs are the new fingers for the GameBoy generation], Accessed June 19, 2014, "...In Japan, the trend was particularly marked. ... under-25s referred to themselves as oya yubi sedai - the thumb generation, or thumb tribe..."</ref> It has been used in politics to identify persons who are not part of the younger generation, such as American politician [[Mitt Romney]], who may have a mobile phone but does not use it dextrously.<ref name=Quinn>MICHELLE QUINN, August 1, 2010, Politico, [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0812/79274.html Mitt Romney not yet a member of the ‘thumb tribe’], Accessed June 19, 2014, "..'I don’t think Romney is a member of the thumb tribe,' said Paul Saffo...</ref><ref name=VanAllen>Amanda VanAllen, Aug 2, 2012, ABC News, [http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/08/the-notes-must-reads-for-thursday-august-02-2012/ Politico’s Michelle Quinn: “Mitt Romney not yet a member of the ‘thumb tribe’”], Accessed June 19, 2014, ".Politico’s Michelle Quinn: “Mitt Romney not yet a member of the ‘thumb tribe’” .."</ref> An effect is that for many young people, the thumb is physically stronger and more flexible, according to researchers.<ref name=BBC>25 March 2002, BBC News, [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1891920.stm Thumbs take over for text generation], Accessed June 19, 2014, "...thumbs of teenagers and young adults have become more widely used than index fingers ... more muscled and dextrous..."</ref> There are medical implications as well; excessive use of thumbs can lead to muscle pain and possible occupational problems.
The term was first used in [[Japan]] to identify the "younger generation of Japanese texters".<ref name=Mindess>Anna Mindess, Intercultural Press, 2006, [https://books.google.com/books?id=dQk1lt0V9foC&pg=PA144&lpg=PA144&dq=%22thumb+tribe%22&source=bl&ots=gO8u3gJPjN&sig=EetSSPDutQnaEKtSExLJNvBqYzs&hl=en&sa=X&ei=aGejU4-cO_ihsASBmYDYBg&ved=0CDgQ6AEwBjgU#v=onepage&q=%22thumb%20tribe%22&f=false Reading Between the Signs], Accessed June 19, 2014, "..The younger generation of Japanese texters, called the thumb tribe...."</ref> Japanese youth used their ''keitai'' or mobile phone to download music, access Japan's version of [[Myspace]] called ''mixi'', surf the web, check train timetables and so forth.<ref>Justin Norrie, April 14, 2007, The Age (Australia), [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2007/04/13/1175971346787.html A nation's youth all thumbs with PCs], Accessed June 19, 2014, "...Like many of her friends and millions of other young Japanese, she appears to use only her "keitai", or mobile phone, to send and receive emails, download music, access mixi (Japan's immensely popular version of Myspace), look at web pages..."</ref> Sometimes it permitted them to form [[smart mob]]s to assemble seemingly spontaneously.<ref name=NYDailyPhoto>March 25, 2008, Brian Dubé, New York Daily Photo, [http://newyorkdailyphoto.com/nydppress/?p=701 Pillow Fight], Accessed June 19, 2014, "..Teenage “thumb tribes” are often cited as the origins of smart mobs..."</ref> The Japanese texting style relied heavily on the thumb, according to a report in ''[[NBC News]]''.<ref name=NBCNews>Yuri Kageyama, Associated Press, July 16, 2008, NBC News, [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25706454/ns/technology_and_science-wireless/t/japan-you-can-probably-find-iphone-there/#.U6NsBlVX9pA Japan: You can probably find an iPhone there], Accessed June 19, 2014, "...The Japanese style of texting relies mainly on a thumb ... users are dubbed "oyayubi zoku" or "thumb tribe."..."</ref>
{{Quote|They've grown up in a world that is dynamically different from the one we lived in. What kind of cars do they want? And what gadgets? They don't even use computers - computers now perceived as going the way of B&W television. At what point do their childhood toys and t'ween technology devices merge? And what future outcomes do they, and marketer-manufacturers expect?|H. Martin Calle, 2007<ref name=AdAge/>}}
